    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9831735,
      "reputation" : 223,
      "user_id" : 7283182,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/9FEKD.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Shubhasish Bhunia",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7283182/shubhasish-bhunia"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 15,
    "last_activity_date" : 1685076294,
    "last_edit_date" : 1685076294,
    "creation_date" : 1624549474,
    "answer_id" : 68118891,
    "question_id" : 23761242,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This can be done using two annotations from Lombok:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://projectlombok.org/features/constructor\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>@RequiredArgsConstructor</code></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://projectlombok.org/features/NonNull\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>@NonNull</code></a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Please find the example as follows:</p>\n<pre><code>package com.ss.model;\n\nimport lombok.*;\n\n@Getter\n@Setter\n@RequiredArgsConstructor\n@ToString\npublic class Employee {\n\n    private int id;\n\n    @NonNull\n    private String firstName;\n\n    @NonNull\n    private String lastName;\n\n    @NonNull\n    private int age;\n\n    @NonNull\n    private String address;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>And then you can create an object as shown below:</p>\n<pre><code>Employee employee = new Employee(&quot;FirstName&quot;, &quot;LastName&quot;, 27, &quot;Address&quot;);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 3446101,
        "reputation" : 21765,
        "user_id" : 2886891,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 75,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/yaE6t.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Honza Zidek",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2886891/honza-zidek"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1707826495,
      "post_id" : 74248934,
      "comment_id" : 137487892,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "IDE generated boilerplate code infests the source code. And whenever you make a change in your class, you must remember to regenerate it again. <code>@AllArgsConstructor</code> doesn&#39;t suffer from this problem."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 20832075,
      "reputation" : 25,
      "user_id" : 15301143,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14GiDzXl2lDUofaSXea3QIpjsprLKHU2H5KMrcVHdAWQ=k-s256",
      "display_name" : "Andrianos Papamarkou",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/15301143/andrianos-papamarkou"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : -1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1667078631,
    "creation_date" : 1667078631,
    "answer_id" : 74248934,
    "question_id" : 23761242,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Lombok is meant to take care of the boilerplate code for your POJOs. Customized constructors/setters/getters/toString/copy etc are not on the boilerplate side of code. For these cases, every Java IDE provide easy to use code generators to help you do things in no time.\nIn your case a</p>\n<pre><code>public MyClass(String firstName, String lastName) {....}\n</code></pre>\n<p>is much more readable and makes more sense than a hypothetic:</p>\n<pre><code>@AllArgsConstructor(exclude = &quot;id&quot;, exclude = &quot;phone&quot;)\n</code></pre>\n<p>Have fun!</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4820459,
      "reputation" : 933,
      "user_id" : 3891283,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 0,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/RoB3Y.gif?s=256",
      "display_name" : "lm2a",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3891283/lm2a"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1691925794,
    "creation_date" : 1691925794,
    "answer_id" : 76893112,
    "question_id" : 23761242,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>When you needs a constructor with just some attributes, you can use</p>\n<p><em><strong>@RequiredArgsConstructor</strong></em> at class level and declare the choosed attributes as final.\nThen, if you need an empty constructor, you can use something like</p>\n<p><em><strong>@NoArgsConstructor(access=AccessLevel.PRIVATE, force=true)</strong></em></p>\n<p>This annotation will create an empty JPA's constructor and the attributes will be initialized with default values (0 for int, null for String and so on).</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<pre><code>@Data\n@Entity\n@Table(name = &quot;VetFiles&quot;)\n@RequiredArgsConstructor\n@NoArgsConstructor(access=AccessLevel.PRIVATE, force=true)\npublic class FileInfo implements Serializable {\n\n    private static final long serialVersionUID = 6719621520531075147L;\n\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)\n    private Integer id;\n\n    private final String name;\n    private final String url;\n\n    @ManyToOne\n    private Thing thing;\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
